  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "The Problem: Uncontrolled Traffic",
      "body": "Without rate limiting, a single client can flood your API with thousands of requests per second — crashing your servers or starving other users.\n\nRate limiting enforces a **maximum request rate** per client.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Token Bucket Algorithm",
      "body": "Imagine a bucket that holds a fixed number of **tokens** (permits):\n- Each request consumes 1 token\n- Tokens **refill at a constant rate** (e.g., 3/second)\n- If bucket is empty → request rejected (HTTP 429)\n\nThe bucket size controls the **burst capacity**.",
      "appearsAtStep": 1,
      "callout": "Burst capacity = bucket size. Sustained rate = refill rate."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Bucket Exhausted → 429",
      "body": "When the bucket empties faster than it refills:\n- New requests arrive but no tokens available\n- Limiter returns **429 Too Many Requests**\n- Client should back off with exponential retry\n\nThe API server is **never overwhelmed** — the limiter absorbs the burst.",
      "appearsAtStep": 4
    },
    {
      "heading": "Token Refill",
      "body": "Tokens refill at the **refill rate** (independent of requests).\n\nCommon strategies:\n- **Per-second**: add N tokens every second\n- **Smooth**: add 1 token every 1/N seconds (avoids micro-bursts)\n\nOnce full, extra tokens are discarded (bucket can't overflow).",
      "appearsAtStep": 5
    },
    {
      "heading": "Steady State vs Overload",
      "body": "**Steady state**: request rate ≤ refill rate → bucket stays partially full, all requests pass.\n\n**Overload**: request rate > refill rate → bucket drains → rejections proportional to the excess.\n\nThe rejected fraction = `(arrival_rate - refill_rate) / arrival_rate`",
      "appearsAtStep": 8
    }
  ],
